int main() {
    std::vector<int> arr;
    arr.push_back(1); // adds 1 at the end of the vector
    arr.push_back(2);
    arr.push_back(3);

    // now you can access elements by their index, or use iterators to traverse the vector
}
```
With `std::vector`, you don't need to worry about manually managing indices or allocating new memory. It's a much more convenient and flexible way to work with dynamic data.

If you're concerned about performance, don't be - `std::vector` is implemented in optimized C++ code and is generally faster than manual array management.

One common approach when working with vectors is to use the `push_back()` method to add new elements at the end of the vector. This way, you don't need to worry about indices or memory allocation.

Of course, if you have a specific reason for using raw arrays, I'd be happy to help with that too! But in general, I highly recommend switching to `std::vector` for dynamic data management.

So, you're wondering whether to use `class` or `typename` for template parameters in C++. Well, here's the thing: they're equivalent in most cases. The choice between them is largely a matter of personal preference or coding style.

However, there are some specific scenarios where one may be preferred over the other. For example, when using template template parameters, you need to use `class` instead of `typename`. This is because `template` itself has an overloaded meaning in this context, and `class` doesn't have that same ambiguity.

Let's take a look at some code examples to illustrate this:

```cpp
// Using class for template template parameter
template <class T>
struct Pair {
    // ...
};

// Using typename for template template parameter (not allowed)
// template <typename T> struct Pair { /* ... */ };
```

As you can see, in the first example, we use `class` to specify the template template parameter. This is because `T` is a dependent name that requires `class` to disambiguate its meaning.

Now, some people prefer to use `typename` consistently throughout their codebase, while others like to use `class` when they're sure that the type parameter will always be a class. It's ultimately up to you and your coding style.

One thing to keep in mind is that `typename` was introduced later in the C++ standard as a way to resolve syntactic ambiguity, but for backward compatibility reasons, `class` kept its overloaded meaning. So, while both keywords are equivalent in most cases, using `typename` can be more accurate and less prone to confusion.

In summary, while there's no hard-and-fast rule that dictates which keyword to use, it's generally a good idea to use `typename` when you're unsure whether the type parameter will always be a class. But if you're consistent in your usage and follow established coding conventions, either keyword is acceptable.

So you want to read a single record from a MySQL database using PHP. I'd recommend using a prepared statement with LIMIT 1 to achieve this.

First, let's assume you have already connected to your MySQL database using `mysqli` or `PDO`. If not, you can use the following code:
```php
$mysqli = new mysqli("localhost", "username", "password", "database");
if ($mysqli->connect_errno) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $mysqli->connect_error);
}
```
Next, let's build a prepared statement with LIMIT 1. For example, if you want to retrieve a record by ID:
```php
$stmt = $mysqli->prepare("SELECT id FROM games WHERE id = ?");
$stmt->bind_param("i", $id);
$stmt->execute();
$result = $stmt->get_result();
```
Here, `$id` is the ID of the record you want to retrieve.

Now, let's use `fetch_assoc()` to retrieve the single record from the result set:
```php
$row = $result->fetch_assoc();
echo $row['id'];
```
This will output the ID of the retrieved record.

One important thing to note is that if there are no records matching the condition, `$row` will be `NULL`. So, you might want to add a check for this:
```php
if ($row !== NULL) {
    echo $row['id'];
} else {
    echo "No record found";
}
```
As for indexing, it's always a good idea to create an index on the column(s) used in your WHERE clause. This can significantly speed up query performance.

Also, if you're using `mysqli`, make sure to select the database before executing any queries:
```php
$mysqli->select_db("games");
```
