To extract POST data, you'll want to use the `req.body` property. However, by default, Express.js (which is a popular Node.js framework) doesn't automatically parse the request body for you. You need to add middleware to your application to enable this functionality.

One common approach is to use the `body-parser` middleware package. Here's an example of how you can install and configure it:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');

const app = express();

app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.use(bodyParser.json());
```
With this setup, the `req.body` property will contain the parsed POST data.

If you're using a newer version of Express.js (4.x or later), you can use the built-in `express.json()` and `express.urlencoded()` middleware functions instead:
```javascript
const express = require('express');

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
```
Once you've added this middleware, you can access the POST data using `req.body`. For example:
```javascript
function (request, response) {
  const postData = request.body;
  console.log(postData); // prints the parsed POST data
}
```
As for file uploads, you'll need to use a library that supports multipart/form-data encoding. One popular option is `multer`, which can be used in conjunction with Express.js:
```javascript
const express = require('express');
const multer = require('multer');

const app = express();

const upload = multer({ dest: './uploads/' });

app.post('/upload', upload.single('file'), function (request, response) {
  const file = request.file;
  console.log(file); // prints the uploaded file information
});
```
In this example, we're using `multer` to handle multipart/form-data uploads. The `upload.single()` method specifies that we expect a single file upload with the name `file`. The uploaded file is then available as `request.file`.

