So you're seeing that your code reads the last line twice, and you want to know why this is happening. The issue lies in how `while (!iFile.eof())` works.

When you read from a file using an `ifstream`, it doesn't immediately check for EOF after reading each line. Instead, it keeps track of whether it's reached the end of the file internally. So when you reach the last line, the EOF flag isn't set yet - only after you try to read again does it become set.

This means that in your loop, when you've just read the last line (30), the EOF flag hasn't been set yet, so the loop continues. Then, on the next iteration, you try to read from the file again, but since you're at the end of the file, this time the EOF flag is indeed set, and the loop exits.

To avoid reading the last line twice, you can modify your code like this:

```cpp
while (iFile >> x) {
    cerr << x << endl;
}
```

In this version, `iFile >> x` will return a reference to `iFile`, which is then used in the loop condition. This means that as soon as you try to read from the file and it's at EOF, the loop will exit immediately.

Alternatively, if you want to keep your original code structure, you can add an extra check after reading each line:

```cpp
while (!iFile.eof()) {
    int x;
    iFile >> x;
    cerr << x << endl;
    if (iFile.eof()) break; // Add this line
}
```

This way, as soon as you reach the end of the file, the loop will exit on the next iteration.

One common approach to avoid these kinds of issues is to use `while (iFile >> x)` instead of checking for EOF explicitly. This way, you don't have to worry about the internal state of the stream, and your code becomes more straightforward and easier to maintain.

